disney_movie_analysis.clean_data_functions module¶

This script takes the raw data and does the data cleaning and organizing.

Returns:

A cleaned Disney Fandom dataframe.

disney_movie_analysis.analysis_functions module¶

This script helps with the analysis.

disney_movie_analysis.analysis_functions.list_averages(dataframe, list_column, summary_column)[source]¶

Takes the averages for each value in a column of lists.

Parameters:

  • dataframe – The pandas dataframe being used.

  • list_column – The column of lists to apply the function on

  • summary_column – The column to take the averages over

Returns:

A pandas dataframe containing the averages for each of the list values.

disney_movie_analysis.analysis_functions.merge_imdb_rt(imdb, rotten_tomatoes)[source]¶

Merge cleaned IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes datasets.

Parameters:

  • imdb – A cleaned IMDB pandas dataframe.

  • rotten_tomatoes – A cleaned Rotten Tomatoes dataframe.

Returns:

A pandas dataframe of the merged IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes dataframes.

disney_movie_analysis.analysis_functions.top_list_vals(column, n)[source]¶

From a list column, returns counts of the frequency of each list value.

Parameters:

  • column – A column of lists in a pandas dataframe in the form df[‘col_name’]

  • n – The number of top values to return

Returns:

A pandas dataframe containing counts of the frequency of the top n values in the list column.

disney_movie_analysis.analysis_functions.year_averages_plot(df, group_column, average_column)[source]¶

Graphs the average of numberic columns through the years.

Parameters:

  • df – The pandas dataframe being used.

  • group_column – The name of a column of to group data by, ie year.

  • average_column – The name of a column to graph the averages of over the groups.

Returns:

None

disney_movie_analysis.scrape_data module¶

This script performs the webscraping and produces the raw dataset to be cleaned.

disney_movie_analysis.scrape_data.get_html_text(bs, name, attrs)[source]¶

A function to get certain text from scraped webpage without causing an error if it does not exist.

Parameters:

  • bs – A beautiful_soup object.

  • name – The name of the html class.

  • attrs – The attributes in the class that we are looking for.

Returns:

The text following the class and attribute if it exists, otherwise an NA.
